151. audieras, etc.= the appli- cation of the parallel.

155. at si, etc.: an indirect proof that riches do not give wisdom.

158. si proprium, etc.: an ex- amination into the nature of prop- erty, in which Horace shows that in both of the two ways in which prop- erty is acquired all the wealth which serves your purposes is really yours. —libra et aere: the conventional form of conveyance at Rome (per aes et libram). This process, a relic of the earlier payment of money by weight, required five Roman citi- zens as witnesses and a weigher (libripens), before whom the par- ties appeared. With a set form of words the buyer claimed the
